* Aerial application
In areas where ground application is not practicable, the fertilizer solutions are applied by aircraft particularly
in hilly areas, in forest lands, in grass lands or in sugarcane fields etc
Aerial application is a technique used in liquid pesticide spraying where the pesticide solution is applied from
an aircraft, typically a plane or helicopter. This technique is commonly used in large-scale agriculture or
forestry operations where ground-based equipment is impractical or too time-consuming.
Weather conditions: Aerial spraying requires calm weather conditions with little to no wind, as wind can
cause the spray to drift off-target and reduce the effectiveness of the treatment. The aircraft should also avoid
flying during rain or high humidity, as this can reduce the droplet size and increase the potential for drift.
Proper dilution: Pesticides need to be mixed with water or other appropriate carriers to achieve the desired
concentration. Follow the instructions on the pesticide label for the recommended dilution rate, which may
vary depending on the pest, crop, and growth stage.
Droplet size: Droplet size is an important factor in aerial spraying, as larger droplets are more likely to reach
the target area and adhere to the plant surface. However, smaller droplets may be more effective in
penetrating plant canopies and reaching pests hiding in the foliage. Adjust the spray nozzles and other
equipment to achieve the desired droplet size based on the target and the pesticide label instructions.
Coverage: Aerial application requires proper coverage of the target area to ensure the pesticide reaches the
pests and other targets. The aircraft should fly at the recommended altitude and speed, and use proper spray
techniques, such as overlapping spray patterns, to achieve uniform coverage.
Safety precautions: Aerial spraying requires additional safety precautions, as the aircraft is flying at a higher
altitude and may be in proximity to people and animals. Follow all safety precautions and guidelines on the
pesticide label to protect yourself, other people, animals, and the environment.
Record-keeping: Maintain proper records of the pesticide used, application rate, weather conditions, and
other relevant information for future reference and to comply with local regulations.
It is essential to follow all local regulations, pesticide labels, and best management practices when using
aerial technique in liquid pesticide spraying. Consulting with a qualified pesticide applicator or agricultural
professional can provide further guidance on proper techniques for aerial spraying.
